@incollection{kavanagh2004definitions,
title = "1 - Open Source Software: Definitions and History",
editor = "Paul Kavanagh",
booktitle = "Open Source Software",
publisher = "Digital Press",
address = "Burlington",
pages = "1 - 17",
year = "2004",
isbn = "978-1-55558-320-0",
doi = "https://doi.org/10.1016/B978-155558320-0/50002-7",
url = "http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B9781555583200500027",
author = "Paul Kavanagh",
abstract = "Publisher Summary
This chapter discusses definitions, frequently asked questions, and historic issues related to open source software. The chapter refers to the software that meets the Open Source Definition (OSD) as “open source.” This is a simple expression that avoids capitalization and acronyms such as “OSS.” The alternatives to open source can be called proprietary software, commercial software, or, alternatively, nonopen, nonfree, or closed software. Open source software must be distributed with a source code included or can easily be available from the Internet. The source code should be in the same form that a programmer would actually use to maintain it. The license of this software will not restrict others from distributing the code or modifications and derived works under the same terms. Some software is offered under different licenses. It may be offered to some groups as open source and to others as closed. To meet the terms of the OSD (to be considered open source), it must be at the user's discretion. This is a hybrid licensing model. The Internet is clearly the “killer application” of open source, as the spreadsheet had been for the personal computer. The Internet has projected open source software into widespread use."
}

